Text.Value: Then you should have killed me rather than saving me.
I intend to cause plenty, but only for our enemies.
But it was not the Prism that held me, and touched my mind and body. That was you.
Kind words do not always come easily to me...
Excellent. Let us teach the cult to fear us.
Someone in this cult might have broken mine, too. We are going to break them back.
You monster.
As you wish.
They broke my mind.
I don't have room for you at the moment.
Moonrise is a den of necromancy, and the most powerful practitioner of the art is Thorm's closest advisor, Balthazar.
I knew you were different to other True Souls when we met, but I could see nothing clearly.
Precisely.
Leave.
I would rather die.
I knew you were different to other True Souls when we lay together. Now I know it was the Prism that silenced the Absolute in those moments, not you.
I won't let that happen.
Then make room. None among your allies can compare to me.
That's in the past.
I can help you fix it.
Of course. You'll be a valuable ally.
We must find the necromancer, and claim what he seeks. Or destroy it.
Now, thanks to the Prism, the Absolute does not cloud my thoughts at all. I see that together, we can have our vengeance on those who infected us.
I am ready to join you in battle, if you have space in your ranks.

EditorData.logicalname: Went to make room in the party

Text.Value: When we lay together, I was myself for the first time since they butchered my mind.
If I leave your side, the Prism will no longer protect me, and I will cease to be Minthara. The Absolute will make me its puppet again.
We have the same goal, and you have a better chance of achieving it with me at your side.
Sleep well. We will venture forth together come morning.
Together we can have our vengeance on those who infected us.
Thank you. For allowing me to come here, and for bringing me back to myself.
Broken minds can heal just as well as broken bones.
It does not compare with the comforts of home, but your camp is almost palatial in comparison to my previous accommodation.
I'm glad you're with me.
Straj.
It is the safest place to be.
General Thorm would have the world believe that his invulnerability is a gift from the Absolute.
Then you shall die.
You're a victim of the cult. Of course I'll protect you.
There is no 'we'. I rescued you, but now you're on your own.
I'll be watching you - don't cause any trouble.
I don't trust you enough to feel safe around you.
Stay with me - you'll be a valuable ally.
|Well enough. I'll take first watch in case any of your other "mercies" come to visit|
I don't think so. You need to leave.
I am no threat to you - I am at your mercy.
Tell me what you know about Ketheric's power first.
It does not need to be. But if you prefer to focus on the fight, I will not distract you.
If your mind is broken, you're no good to me.
Why are you so keen to join with me?
I suspect it is the very relic that Balthazar has been sent to retrieve.
Thank you.
We must eradicate them, starting with General Thorm... I mean Ketheric. My deference to him is a habit that will die hard, I fear.
He has chambers beside the General's, on the upper floor of the tower. I suspect we will find answers there.
Each memory that returns to me is more disturbing than the last. The things that I did in the name of the Absolute... the things that were done to me.
Perhaps later. You should rest for now.
Now that you're free, we can spend more nights together.
|I'll take first watch in case any of your other "mercies" come to visit and we'll set out together in the morning|
You belonged to the Absolute then. I don't even know who you really are.
Swear that you will keep me close... until the Absolute is dead, at least.
The best cure is vengeance, for both of us.
I am.
Strength will not save us from an enemy that can dominate our will.
For now, we will travel together, and fight together. In time, perhaps we will lie together again.
Now, rest. We will need our strength for what lies ahead.
I did not invite you to approach my tent. I need privacy while I recover from my ordeal at Moonrise.
I believe Thorm draws his power not from a divine source, but an arcane one.
The Prism will protect me. You will fight alongside me, and help me to get my vengeance.
And we will break them - it's time for revenge.
Rest well, and keep your wits about you. Tomorrow, we go to war with the cult of the Absolute.
You sound desperate.
Down in their flesh-hives, an Absolutist attacker slashed my mind. I know not who, but I know I seek revenge.
That is a lie, intended to impress those who flock to the cult's cause, and to strike fear in the minds of those who stand against the Absolute.
Yes. Join me.
Fine. You can stay here, but I'll be watching you.
I would gladly join you in the fight. Leave one of your other allies here, and I shall.
Not only this battle, but all that come after.
*And you have earned that trust, along with a small measure of her affection. It is a rare thing, well-hidden in the cold fortress of her mind, and it is precious.*
While our tadpoles live, and the cult have the means to control them, we will never be safe.
As a good leader should.
You'll join me in this battle, then?
You're strong - you'll recover.
All that live can die. I can help you plot Ketheric's demise, but I need something from you first.
Stop grovelling, and leave.
*Her entire being joins with you for a moment, and you see all that she is. Dangerous, cunning, wounded, brutal, paranoid... and utterly loyal to those she trusts.*
The next time we meet, I will kill you. In the Absolute's name, or my own.
Very well. You can join me.
Any suggestions on how we kill an invulnerable man?

Synopsis:
Minthara, now freed from the influence of the Absolute and from a jail cell at Moonrise Towers, joins the players' party at their Camp. She is shaken from her experiences, and is coming to terms with the fact that she now understands the truth about the Absolute - that it is not a god at all, but something monstrous that lies within Moonrise.

She wishes to join with the party, knowing they can help her get vengeance against the cult, and knowing that they are her only hope of salvation, thanks to the Prism that they hold, which shuts out the Absolute's voice.
